recordings.rmk: Unmodified recording, except for replacing 116 seconds with 1 second silence, made from car window. Stopped car to view Northern Harrier that was standing on ground on opposite bank, separated by a 3 meter wide waterway. The hawk flew, but the Dzweet calls that had started before I stopped the car continued. The Swamp Sparrow moved around in the shrub next to the road as it called, and finally popped out in the open where it regarded me curiously momentarily. Plumage appeared fresh, probably a male because it had slight crest. Legs in the sunshine were translucent orange-pink all the way to the toes. Flanks, wings, tail deep russet. Grayish breast with faint blurry streaks. Photo on Flickr.

recordings.loc: Maine (near  Bar Harbor), Hancock County, Maine
recordings.rmk: Bird was seen flying low in grassy marsh habitat on Jesup Path in Acadia National Park. Call was played briefly and bird immediately flew in and perched 3-5 feet from the ground in small shrubs and bushed scattered among marsh grasses. Call was used because Song Sparrows were singing and bird seen briefly flying was a probable Swamp Sparrow. Playback confirmed the initial ID and bird flew around, perching at a few locations before flying back into the tall grass and out of sight.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
High, buzzy "zheet" calls. Bird seen briefly as it flushed into the tall grass. Recorded while out of sight.

# Habitat #
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter. **Precise habitat location** in dense Andropogon virginicus near the forest edge. 

# Editing #
No edits beyond excerpting from longer recording.

recordings.rmk: Not sure if this species is a regular migrant here, seems like strange habitat. We came to this location twice and both times we heard (and sometimes saw) numbers of these birds. This recording was made from two different segments captured during the second visit. Most of the birds were hiding in reeds, weeds, and/or bushes. The few glimpses we caught were not really identifiable as Swamp Sparrow, and I thought they were not red enough (fall plumage) but the call seems to match.
